Now it ſo unluckily fell out, that a young fellow of the Town, having by the help of a Ladder gotten over the Wall, to poſſeſs himſelf of ſome of the delicate Fruit that grew in the Orchard, &c. was at that very Iuncture gotten upon a Tree that hung over the Spring, with its ſpreading branches laden with Fruits, rin'd with Vermilion and Gold; or, as the Poet has it, in Relation to the Garden of the Heſperides:


With Golden Fruits the laden Boughs did bend;

On whom a wakeful Dragon did attend. &c.
